38
00:02:59,840 --> 00:03:04,790
Tonight's programme is all about the
world and the future of computers.

39
00:03:04,840 --> 00:03:08,675
Computers are increasingly
becoming part of our daily lives.

40
00:03:08,720 --> 00:03:10,518
They're used for everything now,

41
00:03:10,560 --> 00:03:13,837
from helping with the resurrection
of King Henry VIII

42
00:03:13,880 --> 00:03:17,430
to the controlling
of Britain's second sun.

43
00:03:17,480 --> 00:03:20,917
But computers, of course,
aren't 100 per cent reliable.

44
00:03:20,960 --> 00:03:22,997
Recently a faulty computer program

45
00:03:23,040 --> 00:03:26,238
was blamed for the disastrous
redecoration of the White House,

46
00:03:26,280 --> 00:03:31,036
which led to computers being banned
in America for three years.

47
00:03:31,080 --> 00:03:33,231
But one thing is certain.

48
00:03:33,280 --> 00:03:35,840
Computers are here to stay.

49
00:03:35,880 --> 00:03:39,669
In fact, experts predict
that by the year 1990,

50
00:03:39,720 --> 00:03:42,599
the number of computers
in Great Britain alone

51
00:03:42,640 --> 00:03:45,712
could be as many as 10,000.

52
00:03:45,760 --> 00:03:47,558
Now, that sounds a lot,

53
00:03:47,600 --> 00:03:50,877
but there's one computer
that's more powerful than them all.

54
00:03:50,920 --> 00:03:53,879
It's Britain's most
technologically advanced computer

55
00:03:53,920 --> 00:03:56,833
and it goes by the name
of Bournemouth.

56
00:03:56,880 --> 00:03:58,712
There he is.

57
00:03:58,760 --> 00:04:00,956
And here to tell us
all about Bournemouth

58
00:04:01,000 --> 00:04:03,390
is the presenter
of BBC's computer programme

59
00:04:03,440 --> 00:04:05,716
and a man who loves
computers so much,

60
00:04:05,760 --> 00:04:09,276
he even changed his name
to Computer Jones.

61
00:04:15,880 --> 00:04:18,236
- Welcome to Look Around You.
- Hello, Peter.

62
00:04:18,280 --> 00:04:21,398
You were involved in the programming
of this computer.

63
00:04:21,440 --> 00:04:23,671
I was its chief programmer,
actually.

64
00:04:23,720 --> 00:04:26,952
Now, you've programmed hundreds
of computers in your career.

65
00:04:27,000 --> 00:04:29,037
What makes Bournemouth so special?

66
00:04:29,080 --> 00:04:33,393
Well, Bournemouth isn't like other
computers because he's so powerful.

67
00:04:33,440 --> 00:04:35,432
In fact, he's so intelligent

68
00:04:35,480 --> 00:04:38,075
he'd look on you and I
as a couple of morons.

69
00:04:38,120 --> 00:04:39,554
- Really?
- Yes.

70
00:04:39,600 --> 00:04:43,389
Which is why the government use him
to sort out their problems.

71
00:04:43,440 --> 00:04:45,432
So what sort of things has he done?

72
00:04:45,480 --> 00:04:49,315
Well, Bournemouth has been involved
in pretty much everything recently.

73
00:04:49,360 --> 00:04:52,239
He helped in the introduction
of the negative currency

74
00:04:52,280 --> 00:04:56,069
and he even assisted the police
in the recent margarine riots.

75
00:04:56,120 --> 00:04:59,318
So he certainly knows how to handle
himself in the real world.

76
00:05:03,520 --> 00:05:06,354
We're really going to put
Bournemouth to the test now

77
00:05:06,400 --> 00:05:09,598
because we've devised
a special Look Around You challenge.

78
00:05:09,640 --> 00:05:12,997
As you can see, we're locking
Bournemouth inside this cage here

79
00:05:13,040 --> 00:05:16,033
and his task is to escape
by the end of the programme.

80
00:05:16,080 --> 00:05:17,070
Thanks.

81
00:05:17,120 --> 00:05:21,160
The cage is made from reinforced
steel so it's extremely secure.

82
00:05:21,680 --> 00:05:25,117
You're gonna need some pretty big
brains to work your way out of this.

83
00:05:25,160 --> 00:05:27,152
Well, best of luck, Bournemouth.

84
00:05:27,200 --> 00:05:30,796
We'll see if he manages to escape
before the end of the show.

85
00:05:30,840 --> 00:05:32,832
(Jack) Good luck, Bournemouth.

86
00:05:56,760 --> 00:05:58,991
(Jack) What's in a name?

87
00:05:59,040 --> 00:06:03,398
Well, letters, but for some of us
it's not that simple.

88
00:06:03,440 --> 00:06:05,830
A recent survey
found that most Britons

89
00:06:05,880 --> 00:06:07,678
had trouble remembering names,

90
00:06:07,720 --> 00:06:11,111
with the name Philip
proving to be the most difficult.

91
00:06:11,160 --> 00:06:13,470
Some things
seem to stay with us for ever.

92
00:06:13,520 --> 00:06:16,080
For example
everyone remembers where they were

93
00:06:16,120 --> 00:06:19,511
when they heard the news that
President Kennedy had been stabbed.

94
00:06:19,560 --> 00:06:23,554
For years scientists have wondered
exactly which part of the brain

95
00:06:23,600 --> 00:06:27,753
is responsible for storing these
so-called permanent remembrances.

96
00:06:27,800 --> 00:06:30,440
And now, with the help of computers,

97
00:06:30,480 --> 00:06:33,837
the part of the brain that labels
some memories as unforgettable

98
00:06:33,880 --> 00:06:37,112
has been identified and utilised
in a new invention

99
00:06:37,160 --> 00:06:40,119
which claims to make forgetfulness
a distant memory.

100
00:06:40,160 --> 00:06:43,756
And it's our Invention of The Week.
It's called the Memory Helmet.

101
00:06:43,800 --> 00:06:48,033
To demonstrate it I'll enlist the
help of our very own Pam Bachelor.

102
00:06:49,000 --> 00:06:50,559
I'm not sure about this.

103
00:06:50,600 --> 00:06:52,637
Don't worry,
it's not as scary as it looks.

104
00:06:52,680 --> 00:06:55,354
- How's your Shakespeare?
- A bit rusty, I'm afraid.

105
00:06:55,400 --> 00:06:58,234
Think you could remember
the titles of all his plays?

106
00:06:58,280 --> 00:07:03,355
Goodness, I can only think of David
and the one about the farm.

107
00:07:03,400 --> 00:07:06,359
In a moment you'll know them all,
guaranteed.

108
00:07:06,400 --> 00:07:08,596
If you could just pop this on.

109
00:07:10,760 --> 00:07:13,116
- Sorry, I won't knock you out.
- It's OK.

110
00:07:13,160 --> 00:07:15,311
- Is that OK?
- Yes, thanks.

111
00:07:15,360 --> 00:07:17,158
I'm going to show you a card

112
00:07:17,200 --> 00:07:20,591
on which is written the titles
of all of Shakespeare's plays,

113
00:07:20,640 --> 00:07:22,438
but just for one second,

114
00:07:22,480 --> 00:07:25,154
and as soon as you see it
I want you to blink.

115
00:07:25,200 --> 00:07:26,714
- OK?
- OK.

116
00:07:26,760 --> 00:07:29,832
- Now, blink.
- Ooh.

117
00:07:29,880 --> 00:07:32,714
Good. That information
is instantly stored

118
00:07:32,760 --> 00:07:34,558
in the helmet's computer chip.

119
00:07:34,600 --> 00:07:37,434
In a moment
it's going to transfer that data

120
00:07:37,480 --> 00:07:41,315
via her optic nerve
into Pam's memory glands.

121
00:07:41,360 --> 00:07:45,320
Now, because of the huge drain
of mental energy on the brain,

122
00:07:45,360 --> 00:07:48,159
this will cause Pam's voice
to lower in pitch,

123
00:07:48,200 --> 00:07:50,032
so don't be alarmed.

124
00:07:50,080 --> 00:07:52,037
Now, let me just turn you on.

125
00:07:52,080 --> 00:07:55,630
I must admit, it's a little bit
fiddly. It's round here somewhere.

126
00:07:55,680 --> 00:07:57,717
- Ow.
- OK, let's just have a look.

127
00:07:59,960 --> 00:08:02,270
- Are you OK, Pam?
- (Deep voice) Yes. Ooh!

128
00:08:02,320 --> 00:08:05,074
Pam Bachelor,
will you please give us the titles

129
00:08:05,120 --> 00:08:09,592
of all of Shakespeare's plays,
starting now?

130
00:08:27,000 --> 00:08:29,356
- Summer In Paris.
- (Buzzer)

131
00:08:29,400 --> 00:08:31,392
- Betty's Revenge.
- (Buzzer)

132
00:08:38,400 --> 00:08:41,359
- Fantastic. Fantastic.
- Well done, Pam, that was great.

133
00:08:41,400 --> 00:08:43,232
- Wasn't that great?
- Impressive.

134
00:08:43,280 --> 00:08:45,840
- Did I get them all?
- 100 per cent.

135
00:08:45,880 --> 00:08:47,360
Thank you very much.

136
00:08:47,400 --> 00:08:49,995
The Memory Helmet
and its inventor Simon Teigh

137
00:08:50,040 --> 00:08:54,910
win a place in the live final of our
Invention of the Year competition

138
00:08:54,960 --> 00:08:56,758
at the end of the series,

139
00:08:56,800 --> 00:09:00,111
where he could be walking away
with this magnificent trophy,

140
00:09:00,160 --> 00:09:04,598
presented by His Royal Highness
Sir Prince Charles.

141
00:09:10,440 --> 00:09:12,750
We've got
some rather disappointing news,

142
00:09:12,800 --> 00:09:16,191
because we've had to stop
the Look Around You challenge.

143
00:09:16,240 --> 00:09:20,314
If you remember, we'd set Britain's
most powerful computer, Bournemouth,

144
00:09:20,360 --> 00:09:22,955
the task of escaping from this cage.

145
00:09:23,000 --> 00:09:25,595
But unfortunately
Bournemouth has broken down

146
00:09:25,640 --> 00:09:27,950
and needs to be repaired
immediately.

147
00:09:28,000 --> 00:09:30,469
This is Eddie Yorque,
our chief technician.

148
00:09:30,520 --> 00:09:32,512
Eddie, if I can stop you
for a moment,

149
00:09:32,560 --> 00:09:34,358
can you tell us what happened?

150
00:09:34,400 --> 00:09:39,839
Yeah, we received a telephone call
from Computer Jones

151
00:09:39,880 --> 00:09:42,315
saying the circuit boards
had overheated...

152
00:09:42,360 --> 00:09:44,192
(Computer) Hang on,
I didn't call you.

153
00:09:44,240 --> 00:09:46,550
Wait a minute,
I know what's happened.

154
00:09:46,600 --> 00:09:49,069
Leave him in his cage, will you?

155
00:09:49,120 --> 00:09:50,713
What has happened?

156
00:09:50,760 --> 00:09:54,276
He's tapped into your telephone
system and impersonated my voice.

157
00:09:54,320 --> 00:09:57,199
- Wow.
- He does a good impression of me.

158
00:09:57,240 --> 00:10:00,312
Listen. Bournemouth, say something.

159
00:10:01,440 --> 00:10:04,194
- What would you like me to say?
- Oh, anything.

160
00:10:04,240 --> 00:10:07,711
(Sighs) Hello,
this is Computer Jones speaking.

161
00:10:07,760 --> 00:10:12,551
I'm 57, I live on my own and I
practise kissing on my Labrador.

162
00:10:12,600 --> 00:10:14,876
- Thank you, Bournemouth.
- That is good.

163
00:10:14,920 --> 00:10:19,039
He called poor Eddie and got him
to take him out of the cage.

164
00:10:19,080 --> 00:10:22,073
- Well, you don't win that easily.
- Oh, really?

165
00:10:22,120 --> 00:10:26,000
Well, it seems that the Look Around
You challenge is back on.

166
00:10:26,040 --> 00:10:28,111
So let's see if Bournemouth
can escape

167
00:10:28,160 --> 00:10:30,550
before the end of the programme.

168
00:10:50,720 --> 00:10:52,791
(Pealy) Everyone loves a good game,

169
00:10:52,840 --> 00:10:56,356
whether it's an exciting
round of Zero-X

