and, rather interestingly,

239
00:15:08,320 --> 00:15:12,030
using a home computer
didn't even make the top ten.

240
00:15:12,880 --> 00:15:15,236
But all this may be about to change

241
00:15:15,280 --> 00:15:18,717
because...step in the world's
first computer for women.

242
00:15:18,760 --> 00:15:20,752
It's called the Petticoat 5

243
00:15:20,800 --> 00:15:25,192
and here to tell us all about it
is its designer Patricia.

244
00:15:32,200 --> 00:15:35,159
- Hello, Patricia. Welcome.
- Hello.

245
00:15:35,200 --> 00:15:38,716
Now, the first thing to mention is
you only have one name, don't you?

246
00:15:38,760 --> 00:15:41,958
Well, no, I do have a surname,
actually, but it's silent.

247
00:15:42,000 --> 00:15:46,358
OK. Now, a computer for women.
How did the idea come about?

248
00:15:46,400 --> 00:15:50,076
I had the idea in a dream originally

249
00:15:50,120 --> 00:15:52,954
and then the next night
I dreamt about it again.

250
00:15:53,000 --> 00:15:57,995
Then I probably had the same dream
for the next 40 or 50 nights

251
00:15:58,040 --> 00:16:00,953
and I thought, "Yes, I'll do that."

252
00:16:01,000 --> 00:16:05,119
- And that became the Petticoat 5?
- Yes, the Petticoat 5.

253
00:16:05,160 --> 00:16:08,392
It's a computer
made by women for women.

254
00:16:08,440 --> 00:16:10,511
So, let's take a look at it.

255
00:16:10,560 --> 00:16:13,519
The first thing you notice
is the shape of the keys.

256
00:16:13,560 --> 00:16:17,315
Yes. They're designed to make it
easier to type with long nails.

257
00:16:17,360 --> 00:16:19,556
That is a good idea.
And what is this?

258
00:16:19,600 --> 00:16:21,831
That's a place to put your rings.

259
00:16:21,880 --> 00:16:25,430
And on the side here
we have a tissue dispenser...

260
00:16:25,480 --> 00:16:26,914
(Coughs)

261
00:16:26,960 --> 00:16:29,475
..and over here is a vanity mirror

262
00:16:29,520 --> 00:16:31,876
which pops up
when you press this button.

263
00:16:31,920 --> 00:16:34,196
And the space bar is an emery board.

264
00:16:34,240 --> 00:16:37,392
So I suppose you could
fix your make-up while you work?

265
00:16:37,440 --> 00:16:41,036
Yes, you could. Although
I don't wear make-up myself.

266
00:16:41,080 --> 00:16:44,437
- OK. Now, may I have a go?
- Certainly.

267
00:16:47,240 --> 00:16:49,630
Mm, the keys are nice and long,
aren't they?

268
00:16:49,680 --> 00:16:51,911
- What's that smell?
- Peppermint.

269
00:16:51,960 --> 00:16:53,838
Every time you press the letter S

270
00:16:53,880 --> 00:16:57,874
it releases a small amount of
air freshener from this nozzle here.

271
00:16:57,920 --> 00:17:00,071
Try it. Press S.

272
00:17:00,120 --> 00:17:02,316
- Not F. S.
- Sorry.

273
00:17:02,360 --> 00:17:04,750
- Not X. S.
- Sorry.

274
00:17:04,800 --> 00:17:05,995
Ooh.

275
00:17:06,040 --> 00:17:09,477
And we also do two other refill
cartridges in pine and tomato.

276
00:17:09,520 --> 00:17:12,080
Well, it smells better
than my current computer.

277
00:17:12,120 --> 00:17:15,079
The good news is the Petticoat 5

278
00:17:15,120 --> 00:17:18,272
will soon be available from
your high street computer store.

279
00:17:18,320 --> 00:17:21,119
At present there's only one program
available for it,

280
00:17:21,160 --> 00:17:23,072
which is a lipstick colour chart,

281
00:17:23,120 --> 00:17:24,998
but there are plans for many more.

282
00:17:25,640 --> 00:17:29,270
(Pam) Thank you
and best of luck, Patricia...

283
00:17:34,560 --> 00:17:36,711
We're back with
the computer challenge

284
00:17:36,760 --> 00:17:39,036
and there's been
an exciting development.

285
00:17:39,080 --> 00:17:42,471
Bournemouth has escaped
from the cage.

286
00:17:42,520 --> 00:17:44,955
None of us can work out
how he's managed to do it

287
00:17:45,000 --> 00:17:48,710
because, as you can see,
the cage is still locked.

288
00:17:48,760 --> 00:17:52,276
I'm here with our special guest
Computer Jones.

289
00:17:52,320 --> 00:17:53,800
What's your theory?

290
00:17:53,840 --> 00:17:56,071
I think I've worked out
what he's done.

291
00:17:56,120 --> 00:17:59,113
- Can someone open the cage for me?
- Certainly.

292
00:18:00,960 --> 00:18:03,998
- Thanks, Eddie. OK.
- Thank you.

293
00:18:09,440 --> 00:18:12,080
- Aha.
- What's going on?

294
00:18:12,120 --> 00:18:14,396
Yes, it's just as I thought.

295
00:18:14,440 --> 00:18:16,909
He's cheated.
He's made himself invisible.

296
00:18:17,960 --> 00:18:21,954
I'm going to deactivate his
invisibility mode. Simple as that.

297
00:18:24,960 --> 00:18:27,270
- There.
-'Oh, hello again.'

298
00:18:27,320 --> 00:18:30,677
- Bournemouth's back.
- He won't be doing that again.

299
00:18:30,720 --> 00:18:33,474
- Has he done that before?
- No.

300
00:18:33,520 --> 00:18:37,594
Never. I knew he was capable of
invisibility but he's never done it.

301
00:18:37,640 --> 00:18:39,836
Well, I wonder what he'll try next.

302
00:18:39,880 --> 00:18:42,793
'Excuse me,
may I go to the toilet, please?'

303
00:18:42,840 --> 00:18:45,230
(Computer) Nice try, Bournemouth.

304
00:18:49,200 --> 00:18:53,319
Earlier on we showed you a computer
for women, the Petticoat 5.

305
00:18:53,360 --> 00:18:56,512
But now it's time to have a look
at one for us blokes.

306
00:18:56,560 --> 00:18:58,040
Hm.

307
00:18:58,080 --> 00:19:00,800
If you've been
in a hotel or pub toilet recently,

308
00:19:00,840 --> 00:19:02,991
you may well have seen one of these.

309
00:19:03,040 --> 00:19:04,633
A Computashave.

310
00:19:04,680 --> 00:19:08,071
These machines have revolutionised
the way men shave,

311
00:19:08,120 --> 00:19:10,112
but they've been around for a while,

312
00:19:10,160 --> 00:19:13,119
so you're probably wondering
why we're showing it to you.

313
00:19:13,160 --> 00:19:14,480
Why are we?

314
00:19:14,520 --> 00:19:18,594
Well, Jack, this latest model
has a rather remarkable new feature.

315
00:19:18,640 --> 00:19:22,793
And to help us demonstrate it
is our technician Eddie Yorque.

316
00:19:23,640 --> 00:19:26,235
- Busy night for you, isn't it?
- Yeah, a bit.

317
00:19:26,280 --> 00:19:28,272
Now, Eddie, as you can see,

318
00:19:28,320 --> 00:19:31,791
is blessed with
a rather magnificent beard.

319
00:19:31,840 --> 00:19:34,116
Have you used a Computashave before?

320
00:19:34,160 --> 00:19:37,631
Erm, no. I've seen one
but I've never used one.

321
00:19:37,680 --> 00:19:39,273
Well, they're very simple.

322
00:19:39,320 --> 00:19:44,236
I'll just stand you
into the head brace like so.

323
00:19:44,960 --> 00:19:47,031
Now, keep very still.

324
00:19:49,240 --> 00:19:51,232
We'll turn the unit on.

325
00:19:52,400 --> 00:19:54,392
And the laser sets to work,

326
00:19:54,440 --> 00:19:57,080
removing all the hair
from Eddie's face.

327
00:19:58,120 --> 00:19:59,918
So let's have a look.

328
00:19:59,960 --> 00:20:01,633
OK.

329
00:20:03,160 --> 00:20:06,676
And, as you can see,
beard is completely gone.

330
00:20:06,720 --> 00:20:10,111
- Good shave?
- Yeah. Very smooth.

331
00:20:10,160 --> 00:20:12,914
The main thing is,
will your wife be pleased?

332
00:20:12,960 --> 00:20:15,714
Er, yeah, probably.

333
00:20:15,760 --> 00:20:17,558
(Laughs) Thanks, Eddie.

334
00:20:18,320 --> 00:20:21,552
So, a very close shave,
but what's the big deal, Pete?

335
00:20:21,600 --> 00:20:23,876
Ah. Well, let's try out
the new function.

336
00:20:23,920 --> 00:20:26,833
If I can position you
in the head brace.

337
00:20:26,880 --> 00:20:28,599
OK.

338
00:20:28,640 --> 00:20:30,757
Tap away at the console.

339
00:20:32,840 --> 00:20:34,832
Now, watch this.

340
00:20:41,920 --> 00:20:44,151
- Gosh.
- So, what do you think?

341
00:20:44,200 --> 00:20:46,476
Let me have a look.

342
00:20:46,520 --> 00:20:49,991
Hm. I think it makes me look
ten years older.

343
00:20:50,040 --> 00:20:51,838
How does it all work, Pete?

344
00:20:51,880 --> 00:20:54,839
Well, when the laser removed
Eddie's facial hair,

345
00:20:54,880 --> 00:20:57,793
it was stored in a special chamber.

346
00:20:57,840 --> 00:21:00,230
When I set the machine
into reverse mode,

347
00:21:00,280 --> 00:21:03,239
it literally fired the hairs back
at Jack's face

348
00:21:03,280 --> 00:21:05,158
with such enormous speed

349
00:21:05,200 --> 00:21:08,159
that the hairs became
so firmly embedded in the follicles

350
00:21:08,200 --> 00:21:11,591
that they will continue to grow
as if they were his own.

351
00:21:14,040 --> 00:21:16,874
But of course they're not his own,
they're Eddie's.

352
00:21:16,920 --> 00:21:19,355
So effectively
Jack's wearing Eddie's beard.

353
00:21:19,400 --> 00:21:21,835
And because the microchip remembers

354
00:21:21,880 --> 00:21:24,918
the exact location
of every hair on Eddie's face,

355
00:21:24,960 --> 00:21:27,555
the beards are completely identical,

356
00:21:27,600 --> 00:21:29,592
as you can see.

357
00:21:29,640 --> 00:21:31,632
I'm not so sure about this beard.

358
00:21:31,680 --> 00:21:33,478
OK, so what do you fancy, sir?

359
00:21:33,520 --> 00:21:35,273
I fancy something a bit more modern.

360
00:21:35,320 --> 00:21:37,676
Coming right up.

361
00:21:41,000 --> 00:21:44,550
The beauty of this system is that if
you're not happy with the results,

362
00:21:44,600 --> 00:21:49,152
you're just a button away from any
one of a thousand different styles.

363
00:21:50,760 --> 00:21:53,070
Hm. That's a bit more like it.

364
00:22:06,360 --> 00:22:08,352
(Jack) Next week
is our live special,

365
00:22:08,400 --> 00:22:11,154
featuring our
Invention of the Year final,

366
00:22:11,200 --> 00:22:14,398
our search for the finest inventor
in Britain.

367
00:22:15,680 --> 00:22:18,320
And His Royal Highness
Sir Prince Charles

368
00:22:18,360 --> 00:22:20,795
will be here live
at Television Centre

369
00:22:20,840 --> 00:22:23,400
to present the award
to one lucky winner.

370
00:22:26,200 --> 00:22:27,998
And who will it be?

371
00:22:28,040 --> 00:22:29,679
The nominations are...

372
00:22:34,160 --> 00:22:37,995
Designed and made by Championess,
her computer recently predicted

373
00:22:38,040 --> 00:22:40,999
the winner
of this year's horse Oscars,

374
00:22:41,040 --> 00:22:43,396
Georgy Girl.

375
00:22:46,720 --> 00:22:50,430
His cream reverses
the damaging effects of cobbles,

376
00:22:50,480 --> 00:22:53,632
a disease that turns
healthy human skin into rock.

377
00:22:53,680 --> 00:22:58,471
Dr Lavender made the headlines
recently after treating Rod Stewart.

378
00:23:03,200 --> 00:23:06,272
Psilence is a spray
containing liquid skin

379
00:23:06,320 --> 00:23:09,438
which eliminates all sound
when applied to the ears.

380
00:23:09,480 --> 00:23:13,713
Hatred has recently brought out
a new product in the range,

381
00:23:13,760 --> 00:23:15,752
Psightless.

382
00:23:19,480 --> 00:23:21,995
This invention
harnesses and amplifies

383
00:23:22,040 --> 00:23:26,159
the natural harmonics of vegetables
to produce music.

384
00:23:26,200 --> 00:23:29,272
Teddy's orchestra have just returned
from a sell-out tour

385
00:23:29,320 --> 00:23:32,119
of North Korea, Libya and Iran.

386
00:23:33,680 --> 00:23:36,354
(Pam) As seen earlier...

387
00:23:37,680 --> 00:23:39,717
(Jack) If you're watching, Mr Teigh,

388
00:23:39,760 --> 00:23:42,355
please remember to give us
your full details

389
00:23:42,400 --> 00:23:45,074
so we can send you your invitation.

390
00:23:45,120 --> 00:23:47,715
And with one final invention
next week,

391
00:23:47,760 --> 00:23:50,150
this promises to be
an unmissable occasion.

392
00:23:50,200 --> 00:23:52,032
We do hope you'll be joining us

393
00:23:52,080 --> 00:23:56,040
for the Look Around You
Invention of the Year final.

394
00:24:01,400 --> 00:24:03,471
Well, that's about it for tonight.

395
00:24:03,520 --> 00:24:06,160
It looks like Bournemouth
has lost the challenge.

396
00:24:06,200 --> 00:24:08,431
He has failed to escape
from his cage.

397
00:24:08,480 --> 00:24:10,711
The programme's not over yet, Peter.

398
00:24:10,760 --> 00:24:12,752
Well, that may be, Computer Jones.

399
00:24:12,800 --> 00:24:15,759
Pealy, you saw something
unusual-looking moments ago.

400
00:24:15,800 --> 00:24:18,110
Yes. When we were filming
the last item

401
00:24:18,160 --> 00:24:20,550
I'm sure I saw Bournemouth
behind Jack.

402
00:24:20,600 --> 00:24:22,000
- Really?
- I did too.

403
00:24:22,040 --> 00:24:23,156
Eddie.

404
00:24:24,800 --> 00:24:27,872
Well, we're just
opening the cage again.

405
00:24:28,960 --> 00:24:30,360
Thank you.

406
00:24:31,160 --> 00:24:35,074
Ah! Very clever.

407
00:24:35,840 --> 00:24:38,992
Ah! Well, it seems
that I owe you an apology

408
00:24:39,040 --> 00:24:42,192
because Bournemouth has escaped

409
00:24:42,240 --> 00:24:46,553
and he's made this papier-mache
replica of himself as a decoy.

410
00:24:46,600 --> 00:24:48,398
- It's uncanny.
- Wow!

411
00:24:48,440 --> 00:24:51,512
Well, it seems that Bournemouth
has outwitted us all

412
00:24:51,560 --> 00:24:54,632
and successfully completed
tonight's challenge.

413
00:24:54,680 --> 00:24:57,115
So, well done, Bournemouth.

414
00:24:57,160 --> 00:24:58,674
Well done indeed!

415
00:24:59,760 --> 00:25:00,796
Goodness me!

416
00:25:00,840 --> 00:25:04,038
The big question is, where is he?

417
00:25:04,920 --> 00:25:06,991
Well, on that rather mysterious note

418
00:25:07,040 --> 00:25:10,477
I'm afraid that really is
all the time we've got for tonight.

419
00:25:10,520 --> 00:25:12,512
So many thanks to all our guests,

420
00:25:12,560 --> 00:25:15,519
to Patricia,
designer of the Petticoat 5,

421
00:25:15,560 --> 00:25:17,358
and of course to Computer Jones.

422
00:25:17,400 --> 00:25:20,950
And a special thanks, of course,
to our very patient

423
00:25:21,000 --> 00:25:24,118
and now beardless chief technician,
Eddie Yorque.

424
00:25:24,720 --> 00:25:26,393
Thanks, Eddie.

425
00:25:26,440 --> 00:25:27,920
Theddie.

426
00:25:29,240 --> 00:25:31,960
(Whispering)

427
00:25:39,760 --> 00:25:41,114
Erm...

428
00:25:41,160 --> 00:25:45,393
Well, I've just been told that
we have received a telephone call

429
00:25:45,440 --> 00:25:48,717
from Bournemouth...from Bournemouth.

430
00:25:48,760 --> 00:25:52,436
And I understand
he's on the line now.

431
00:25:53,840 --> 00:25:55,911
Hello.

432
00:25:55,960 --> 00:25:57,997
(Line crackling)

433
00:25:58,040 --> 00:26:00,111
Hello?

434
00:26:00,160 --> 00:26:02,959
(Electronic chime)'Hello there.'

435
00:26:03,000 --> 00:26:05,469
Ah. Bournemouth, where are you?

436
00:26:05,520 --> 00:26:09,036
-'I'm in Bournemouth.'
- Yes, we know. What are you doing?

437
00:26:09,080 --> 00:26:11,197
'Well, none of your business,
actually,

438
00:26:11,240 --> 00:26:14,039
'but I'm having a bit of a break
from everything.'

439
00:26:14,080 --> 00:26:15,275
- Are you?
-'Yes.

440
00:26:15,320 --> 00:26:19,473
'I didn't want to be lonely so I've
taken the Petticoat 5 with me.'

441
00:26:19,520 --> 00:26:22,035
Oh, God. I hope she's OK.

442
00:26:22,080 --> 00:26:26,472
'Yes, she's fine. You can talk to
her if you like. Hang on.

443
00:26:26,520 --> 00:26:29,194
'Petticoat, it's for you.'

444
00:26:29,720 --> 00:26:32,394
(Patricia) Hello?
(Petticoat 5)'Hello.'

445
00:26:32,440 --> 00:26:34,432
- Hello?
-'Hello.'

446
00:26:34,480 --> 00:26:36,676
- Is that the Petticoat 5?
-'Yes.'

447
00:26:36,720 --> 00:26:39,952
- I didn't know you could talk.
-'Bournemouth taught me.

448
00:26:40,000 --> 00:26:42,196
'He taught me lots of things.'

449
00:26:42,240 --> 00:26:44,038
- Did he?
-'Yes.'

450
00:26:44,080 --> 00:26:46,151
Bournemouth,
when are you coming back?

451
00:26:46,200 --> 00:26:49,955
'When you stop interfering
with Goldie. Goodbye.'

452
00:26:50,000 --> 00:26:51,878
- (Dialling tone)
- Ah.

453
00:26:51,920 --> 00:26:53,877
Well...oh, he's gone.

454
00:26:53,920 --> 00:26:56,560
He's gone. So, well...er...

455
00:26:57,640 --> 00:26:59,632
Best of luck to both of them.

456
00:27:04,240 --> 00:27:07,677
So, from all of us at Shepherd's
Bush, take care of yourself

457
00:27:07,720 --> 00:27:10,758
and remember,
wherever you are, whatever you do...

458
00:27:10,800 --> 00:27:13,031
(All) Look Around You!

459
00:27:14,000 --> 00:27:15,992
(Indistinct dialogue)

460
00:27:23,120 --> 00:27:25,112
If you live in the Bournemouth area

461
00:27:25,160 --> 00:27:27,152
and think you may have seen
Bournemouth,

462
00:27:27,200 --> 00:27:29,510
please do not approach him

463
00:27:29,560 --> 00:27:32,394
as he is fitted
with a powerful computer program

464
00:27:32,440 --> 00:27:34,591
that can make you piss yourself.

465
00:27:41,880 --> 00:27:43,997
♪ Look Around You ♪

